/-
We have proven that for any set of distinct primes $p_1, \dots, p_k$, there are infinitely many
integers $n$ such that $n!$ is divisible by an even power of each $p_i$. This answers the user's
question in the affirmative. The proof follows the strategy from the provided paper (Berend 1997),
using the recurrence of valuation vectors and the existence of zero-sum subsets in $(Z/2Z)^k$.
Specifically, we constructed "rich blocks" of valuation vectors that allow generating any subset
sum, and used this to extend any solution $N$ to a larger solution $N'$.
-/

